english:
  title: The Solitary Bridge
  author: Kim Siseup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A small bridge cuts across the emerald wave's face.
    A wanderer crosses the shimmering mountain mist, while jade-green depths deepen.
    On both banks, moss-flowers drink the rain and glisten,
    and autumn's light on each peak leans upon the clouds, turning cool.

    The stream's voice speaks the wordless dharma,
    the pine's song plays the ancient lute.

    If I venture further, the hermit's chamber cannot be far—
    where monkeys cry and the moon shines white:
    that is the Eastern Grove.
  footnotes:
    - The 'wordless dharma' (무생의 법문) refers to Buddhist teaching transmitted beyond words, suggesting the natural world as a teacher of enlightenment.
    - The Eastern Grove (동림) likely references a sacred Buddhist site, possibly Dongrim Temple, representing a spiritual destination.
    - This poem exemplifies the Sijo poet's meditation on nature as a path to transcendence, blending Buddhist philosophy with landscape imagery.
